  <!-- S9 IS A GREY RIGHT FOR YOU — self-assessment moat -->
  <section id="fit-you">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Is an African Grey Right for You?</h2>
    <a class="inf" href="/blog/is-african-grey-good-for-beginners/"><img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-owner-fit-scorecard.webp" srcset="/african-grey-owner-fit-scorecard-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-owner-fit-scorecard.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="A self-assessment scorecard for deciding if an African Grey is right for you, six readiness questions with a meter" loading="lazy"></a>
    <p>The question behind every pros-and-cons list is personal: would an African Grey actually thrive in your home, with your hours and your noise tolerance? The self-assessment below turns the honest answer into ten minutes of thinking instead of ten years of regret.</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">Score Your Household Honestly</h3>
    <p>No breeder can tell you whether a Grey fits your life — but six honest questions can. Tick the ones that are genuinely true for your household, then read your score. There are no wrong answers, only a clearer decision.</p>
    <div class="quiz-tool" data-label="Self-assessment · are you Grey-ready?">
      <div class="quiz-q" role="group" aria-label="Readiness checklist">
        <label><input type="checkbox" class="fit-ck"> Someone is home most of the day, most days</label>
        <label><input type="checkbox" class="fit-ck"> I can give a bird several hours of attention daily</label>
        <label><input type="checkbox" class="fit-ck"> I can plan for a 40–60 year commitment, caretaker included</label>
        <label><input type="checkbox" class="fit-ck"> My household tolerates noise and can handle powder-down dust</label>
        <label><input type="checkbox" class="fit-ck"> I have budget for setup, quality food and an avian vet</label>
        <label><input type="checkbox" class="fit-ck"> I have parrot experience, or I have genuinely done the research</label>
      </div>
      <button type="button" class="btn-clay quiz-btn" id="fit-btn">See my readiness</button>
      <p class="quiz-result" id="fit-result" hidden></p>
    </div>
    <h4 class="cag-h4">Time, Home, Budget, and Noise Questions</h4>
    <p>The four that sink most placements are time at home, daily attention, the decades-long horizon, and honesty about noise and dust. If those four are shaky, the other two rarely save it.</p>
    <h5 class="cag-h5">How to Read Your Score</h5>
    <p>Five or six ticks and a Grey is a realistic, rewarding choice. Three or four and it is a maybe worth closing the gaps first. Two or fewer, and the kind thing — for you and the bird — is to wait or choose a lower-need companion.</p>
    <h6 class="cag-h6">Breeder note: the honest cutoff</h6>
    <p>We have gently talked buyers out of a Grey more than once. A sale we turn down beats a bird we take back — that is the whole point of a self-assessment you fill in before you fall in love with a photo.</p>
  </section>

