  <!-- S10 WHO SHOULD NOT -->
  <section id="not-for">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Who Should NOT Get an African Grey?</h2>
    <a class="inf" href="/african-grey-parrot-care-guide/"><img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/who-should-not-get-african-grey.webp" srcset="/who-should-not-get-african-grey-760.webp 760w, /who-should-not-get-african-grey.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="A who-should-not-own-an-African-Grey checklist of honest disqualifiers for prospective owners" loading="lazy"></a>
    <p>We turn buyers away more often than people expect, because a Grey in the wrong home becomes a plucking, screaming, rehomed bird. If any of the profiles below describes your household today, the kindest decision is a different pet — or a later date.</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">Households This Bird Will Struggle In</h3>
    <p>The honest disqualifiers, said plainly. This bird is not for you if you travel most weeks, want a quiet apartment pet, expect small children to be the main handlers, want something low-maintenance, are buying an impulse gift, or cannot plan four decades ahead. None of that makes you a bad owner — it makes a Grey the wrong bird.</p>
    <div class="choose-grid">
      <div class="choose-c too">
        <div class="choose-h"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="20" height="20" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M18 6 6 18M6 6l12 12"/></svg>A Grey is the wrong bird if…</div>
        <ul class="choose-list chev">
          <li>You travel most weeks or work long days away from home</li>
          <li>You want a quiet, hands-off apartment pet</li>
          <li>Small children will be the primary handlers</li>
          <li>You want a low-maintenance, forgiving first pet</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="choose-c grey">
        <div class="choose-h"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="20" height="20" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M20 6 9 17l-5-5"/></svg>A Grey can work if…</div>
        <ul class="choose-list tick">
          <li>Someone is home for most of the day</li>
          <li>You accept a decades-long, evolving commitment</li>
          <li>You have done the research or have parrot experience</li>
          <li>You budget for enrichment, good food and an avian vet</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <h4 class="cag-h4">The Impulse-Buy Warning</h4>
    <p>The most common failed placement starts with a talking video and a "let's just do it" decision. A Grey bought on impulse is the Grey most likely to end up plucked, screaming or rehomed. If any part of this decision feels rushed, that feeling is the answer.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-header-logo-160.webp" width="54" height="54" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S11 WHO THRIVES -->
  <section id="thrives">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Who Actually Thrives With an African Grey?</h2>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img og" src="/spoonfed-african-grey-baby-for-sale.webp" srcset="/spoonfed-african-grey-baby-for-sale.webp 640w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="A hand-raised African Grey chick spoon-fed by its breeder, the household type that thrives with a Grey" loading="lazy" style="object-position:center 38%">
    <p>The flip side matters just as much: certain households and African Greys fit like lock and key. If you recognise yourself below, a Grey is not a gamble for you — it is arguably the best companion bird you could choose.</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">The Owners Who Do Best</h3>
    <p>Flip every disqualifier and you get the owner who flourishes. In our placements, the happiest homes share a shape — present, patient, and honest with themselves about the work before the bird ever arrived.</p>
    <h4 class="cag-h4">What They Have in Common</h4>
    <p>Retirees and work-from-home owners, experienced bird keepers, and calm adult households top the list. So do people open to an older rehomed bird; our <a href="/african-grey-adoption/">African Grey adoption page</a> frames when a settled adult beats a baby for the right owner.</p>
    <h5 class="cag-h5">The Households That Thrive</h5>
    <p>Present most of the day, tolerant of noise and mess, financially steady, and treating the bird as a decades-long family member rather than a novelty — that is the profile, again and again.</p>
    <h6 class="cag-h6">Breeder note: what we see in our real placements</h6>
    <p>The owners who send us the happiest year-two updates are rarely the ones who wanted the flashiest talker. They are the ones who wanted a companion and understood, going in, exactly what that would cost in time.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-header-logo-160.webp" width="54" height="54" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S12 CONSERVATION / SHOULD THEY BE KEPT -->
  <section id="ethics">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Should African Greys Even Be Kept as Pets?</h2>
    <a class="inf" href="/cites-african-grey-documentation/"><img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-captive-bred-vs-wild-caught.webp" srcset="/african-grey-captive-bred-vs-wild-caught-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-captive-bred-vs-wild-caught.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="A captive-bred vs wild-caught African Grey contrast showing a documented aviary bird beside a prohibited wild-capture symbol" loading="lazy"></a>
    <p>It is a fair challenge, and conservation groups raise it for good reason: wild African Grey populations are endangered precisely because of trapping for the pet trade. The honest answer separates wild-caught birds from documented captive breeding — completely.</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">The Wild-Capture Argument, Taken Seriously</h3>
    <p>It is a fair question, and welfare groups raise it honestly: wild African Grey populations have been hit hard by trapping, and the species is genuinely threatened. We will not wave that away — a wild-caught bird in the pet trade is a real harm, and no breeder worth trusting pretends otherwise.</p>
    <h4 class="cag-h4">Captive-Bred Is the Opposite of Wild-Caught</h4>
    <p>The distinction is the whole answer. A documented, captive-bred Grey was hatched in a home aviary, takes no bird from the wild, and stands apart from the trapping that harms wild flocks — the same logic behind every <a href="/captive-bred-african-grey-parrot/">captive-bred African Grey</a> we raise.</p>
    <h5 class="cag-h5">What Captive-Bred, CITES-Documented Actually Means</h5>
    <p>Because the African Grey sits at CITES Appendix I, captive-bred paperwork is what makes a domestic sale legal at all. Our CITES documentation page walks the full paper trail — a closed leg band, hatch record and captive-bred certificate that a wild-caught bird can never produce.</p>
    <h6 class="cag-h6">Citation: CITES Appendix I and captive-bred status</h6>
    <p><a href="https://cites.org/eng/app/appendices.php" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CITES ↗</a> lists the African Grey (Psittacus erithacus) on Appendix I, the framework under which captive-bred birds are legally kept and wild-caught trade is prohibited.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-header-logo-160.webp" width="54" height="54" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

