  <!-- S14 BEGINNERS — verdict + link out (no re-teach) -->
  <section id="beginners">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Are African Greys Good for Beginners?</h2>
    <a class="inf" href="/blog/is-african-grey-good-for-beginners/"><img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/is-african-grey-good-for-beginners-verdict.webp" srcset="/is-african-grey-good-for-beginners-verdict-760.webp 760w, /is-african-grey-good-for-beginners-verdict.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="An African Grey for beginners verdict gauge with the needle resting on intermediate" loading="lazy"></a>
    <p>Can a first-time bird owner handle an African Grey? Our honest answer: rarely — a Grey punishes under-preparation like no other companion parrot. But rarely is not never, and the difference is preparation you can actually measure.</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">The Short Answer for First-Time Owners</h3>
    <p>The verdict: for most first-timers, an African Grey is an intermediate-to-advanced bird, not a starter pet — its intelligence and sensitivity punish under-preparation. A committed beginner who has genuinely done the homework can still succeed. Because experience level deserves its own honest treatment, our full guide on whether an African Grey suits a first-time owner covers it properly rather than us repeating it here.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-header-logo-160.webp" width="54" height="54" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S15 COST -->
  <section id="cost">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">What Does an African Grey Really Cost?</h2>
    <a class="inf" href="/african-grey-parrot-price/"><img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-first-year-and-lifetime-cost.webp" srcset="/african-grey-first-year-and-lifetime-cost-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-first-year-and-lifetime-cost.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="An African Grey cost of ownership receipt covering purchase, cage, food and vet with a shipping-tier footer" loading="lazy"></a>
    <p>The purchase price is the smallest number in African Grey ownership. Between the cage, the avian vet, the diet and forty-plus years of upkeep, the real question is whether the lifetime budget fits — so here it is, itemised the way we lay it out for our own buyers.</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">Purchase, First Year, and Lifetime</h3>
    <p>Our African Grey price guide breaks it down bird by bird, but the shape is simple: a documented Congo runs $1,700–$3,500 and a Timneh $1,500–$1,600 from a licensed U.S. breeder, before $185 airport or $350 home-delivery shipping — then cage, quality food, enrichment and avian-vet care every year after. Cost is a con most buyers underestimate.</p>
    <h4 class="cag-h4">Why a Suspiciously Low Price Is a Warning</h4>
    <p>Price is a signal, not just a number. A Congo advertised at $800 is not a bargain a real aviary can offer and survive — it is the bait behind deposit-and-vanish scams. When a discount looks impossible, it is.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-header-logo-160.webp" width="54" height="54" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S16 LIFESPAN -->
  <section id="lifespan">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">The 40 to 60 Year Lifespan, Planned Honestly</h2>
    <a class="inf" href="/african-grey-parrot-lifespan/"><img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/african-grey-40-60-year-lifespan-timeline.webp" srcset="/african-grey-40-60-year-lifespan-timeline-760.webp 760w, /african-grey-40-60-year-lifespan-timeline.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="An African Grey lifespan timeline ribbon from weaning to sixty years with life-stage milestones" loading="lazy"></a>
    <p>How long do African Greys live? Forty to sixty years with proper care — a lifespan that reshapes the decision entirely. A Grey is not a pet you own for a chapter of life; it is a companion you plan a life around.</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">Building a Bird Into Your Long-Term Life</h3>
    <p>The lifespan is the pro and the con fused into one line: decades of companionship, and decades of responsibility. Our African Grey lifespan guide covers the succession planning — a named caretaker, a care fund, instructions in writing — that turns "a bird that can outlive you" from a worry into a plan. Handle that, and the longest commitment becomes the best part of owning a Grey.</p>
  </section>

  <div class="seam"><img src="/cag-header-logo-160.webp" width="54" height="54" alt="" loading="lazy"></div>

  <!-- S17 NOISE DANDER CARE — compact callout, no image -->
  <section id="care">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Noise, Dander and Daily Care — the Unfiltered Truth</h2>
    <p>Every species has a maintenance reality its admirers gloss over. For the African Grey it is powder-down dust, a daily attention requirement measured in hours, and a voice that, while quieter than a cockatoo's, is never silent.</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">What Day-to-Day Living Really Sounds and Looks Like</h3>
    <p>Day to day, a Grey is a talker with a fine dust habit and a standing appointment for your time. Expect conversational chatter and mimicked household sounds, sharper contact calls when it wants you, a film of powder-down dander on nearby surfaces, and a cage that needs frequent cleaning. An air purifier, regular bathing and a fixed routine keep all of it manageable — our <a href="/african-grey-parrot-care-guide/">African Grey care guide</a> covers the daily rhythm in full. None of it is a surprise to a prepared owner; all of it blindsides an unprepared one.</p>
  </section>

